<dl>
  <dt class="expand">Discussion 07 (May 10 and 11, 2022): The
  Copenhagen Interpretation</dt>
  <div class="collapse"><dd>
      <p>Pre-class:</p>
      <ul>
	<li>Read section 3.2 from <a href="http://www.jimbaggott.com/"
	  target="blank">Jim Baggott</a>, The Meaning of Quantum
	  Theory, Oxford University Press, 1992.</li>
	<li>Optionally, if you want another (perhaps simpler and more
	quantum-focused) synopsis of the positivism of the early
	1920s, read section 3.1.  This is pages 75-81.</li>
	<li>Here are some goals for our discussion:
	  <ul>
	    <li>The main thing to focus on is the Copenhagen
	    interpretation, which is the standard interpretation of
	      quantum mechanics.</li>
	    <li>We can also discuss the EPR paradox and Bell's 
	    inequalities, which we'll have covered in class on
	    Monday. I suspect there'll be a lot to talk about and
	    ponder.</li>
	  </ul>
	<li>I think you should find this reading shorter and more
	accessible than last week's reading.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>In-class content:</p>
      <ul>
	<li>Handouts: None</li>
      </ul>
    </dd>
